Difference between Git fetch and Git pull

The key difference is that git fetch only downloads changes from the remote repository without touching your working files, while git pull downloads and immediately integrates those changes into your current branch (via merge or rebase).

-->git fetch is like checking what’s new on the remote repo without touching your local work. It downloads all the latest commits, branches, and tags from the remote into your local .git folder, but it doesn’t change your working files 
   or your current branch. You can then inspect those changes with commands like git log origin/main or git diff main origin/main.
-->git pull is basically git fetch + git merge (or rebase, depending on your config). It not only downloads the changes but also immediately tries to integrate them into your current branch. That’s why you sometimes see merge conflicts 
   when you run git pull.

Think of it like this:
git fetch → “Bring me the news, but don’t act on it yet.”
git pull → “Bring me the news and apply it right now.”

👉 Best practice:
Use git fetch when you want to review changes first before merging.
Use git pull when you’re confident and just want to update quickly.

